<docroot>
  <refentry>
    <!-- gpgkey -->
    <refsect2>
      <title>&lt;gpgkey&gt;</title>
      <para>
      Some RPMs are signed with a gpgkey, allowing end users to validate their
      contents.  The gpgkey element points to an exported RPM GPG public key that
      can be used to validate a repository's RPMs.
      </para>
      <programlisting>
element gpgkey {
  attribute check { text },
  text
}
      </programlisting>
      <refsection>
        <title>Attributes</title>
        <para>gpgkey elements have the following attributes:</para>
        <refsection>
          <title>check</title>
          <para>
          optional; boolean value indicating whether or not to actually check the
          RPMs against this key; defaults to 'false'
          </para>
        </refsection>
      </refsection>
      <refsection>
        <title>Parents</title>
        <para>repo</para>
      </refsection>
    </refsect2>
    
    <!-- repodata-path -->
    <refsect2>
      <title>&lt;repodata-path&gt;</title>
      <para>
      repodata-path is a path, relative to a repo's &lt;path&gt; element, where the
      'repodata' folder of the repository can be found.  This element is optional;
      if not present, '.' is assumed
      </para>
      <programlisting>
element repodata-path { text }
      </programlisting>
      <refsection>
        <title>Parents</title>
        <para>repo</para>
      </refsection>
    </refsect2>
    
    <!-- repos -->
    <refsect2>
      <title>&lt;repos&gt; (top level)</title>
      <para>
      The repos element contains configuration data regarding the source repositories
      from which to gather RPMs for the custom distribution.  It lists each
      repository separately, along with any and all information required to download
      files from it (such as username/password for https locations).
      </para>
      <para>
      The repos container must contain exactly one repo with type 'base'; this
      indicates that this repository should be used as the source for several other
      important distribution files, including group files, stage 2 images, and
      isolinux files.  There can be any number of any other type of repo.
      </para>
      <programlisting>
element repos {
  element repo { attribute type { 'base' } ... }
  element repo { ... }*
}
      </programlisting>
      <refsection>
        <title>Parents</title>
        <para>distro</para>
      </refsection>
      <refsection>
        <title>Examples</title>
        <para>
        A repos element consists of multiple repo elements; see repo for an example
        of repo elements.
        </para>
      </refsection>
    </refsect2>
    
  </refentry>
</docroot>
